<Base
  title="Latent Control States · Xiaochuan Li"
  description="From behavioral evidence to mechanism: do prompt-framing effects correspond to causally relevant states in activation space, or to surface features that merely travel with the prompt?"
>
  <article class="prose">
    <div class="text-xs uppercase tracking-wider text-[var(--color-text-dim)] font-medium mb-2">
      Extension · mechanistic bridge
    </div>
    <h1>Latent Control States under prompt framing</h1>
    <p class="text-[var(--color-text-muted)] italic !text-lg !mb-8">
      A mechanistic extension of the behavioral causal-evidence program.
    </p>

    <p>
      This project is the mechanistic extension of the behavioral program: if a behavioral
      intervention reveals a causal control state, can we find a corresponding state or direction in
      activation space?
    </p>

    <p>
      The target is not to replace the core sequence, but to connect its behavioral evidence to
      mechanism when that is possible. Planned methods include probing, sparse autoencoders,
      activation patching, and steering; the role of those tools is to test whether a behaviorally
      identified control state has an internal counterpart, or whether the apparent control travels
      only with surface prompt features.
    </p>

    <p>
      In the roadmap, Latent Control States sits after the core behavioral sequence as a mechanistic
      bridge from causal evidence over behavior to activation-space hypotheses.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>
